---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import PageHeader from '../../components/sections/PageHeader.astro';
import RelatedContent from '../../components/sections/RelatedContent.astro';
import CTABand from '../../components/sections/CTABand.astro';
import { buildBreadcrumbSchema, buildArticleSchema, buildFAQSchema } from '../../lib/schema';

const title = 'Packaging Cost Drivers: What Changes a Box Quote in Canada';
const description = 'A practical buyer guide to packaging cost drivers in Canada: size, material, print, tooling, MOQ, sampling, freight, and reorder planning.';
const url = '/blog/packaging-cost-drivers-box-quote-canada';
const datePublished = '2026-07-05';
const image = '/images/blog/packaging-cost-drivers-box-quote-canada-generated.png';

const breadcrumb = buildBreadcrumbSchema([
  { name: 'Home', url: '/' },
  { name: 'Blog', url: '/blog' },
  { name: 'Packaging Cost Drivers', url }
]);
const article = buildArticleSchema({ title, description, url, datePublished, author: 'Apex Packaging Solutions' });
const faq = buildFAQSchema([
  { q: 'What affects custom packaging cost the most?', a: 'Size, material, order quantity, print coverage, tooling, finishing, freight, sampling, and the complexity of inserts or special structures usually have the biggest impact.' },
  { q: 'Does a higher MOQ always lower the price?', a: 'A higher quantity usually lowers the unit price, but it can increase cash tied up in inventory. The best quantity balances unit cost, storage, forecast accuracy, and reorder timing.' },
  { q: 'How can buyers get a faster packaging quote?', a: 'Send dimensions, product weight, quantity, material preference, artwork status, print requirements, delivery location, and target date in the first request.' }
]);
---
<BaseLayout title="Packaging Cost Drivers Canada" description={description} image={image} schemaBlocks={[breadcrumb, article, faq]}>
  <PageHeader
    eyebrow="Knowledge base · Packaging quotes"
    heading="Packaging cost drivers - what changes a custom box quote in Canada."
    lead="A packaging quote changes when the structure, board, print, finish, quantity, sampling, freight, or timeline changes. A cleaner RFQ helps buyers compare the real cost, not just the first unit price."
    imageSrc={image}
    imageAlt="Premium Apex Packaging quote desk with custom boxes, material swatches, print finishes, and packaging cost worksheet."
  />

  <section class="py-12 md:py-20">
    <div class="container max-w-default prose-apex">
      <p><strong>Packaging cost drivers</strong> matter because two quotes that look similar may not include the same assumptions. One supplier may price a simple kraft shipper, another may assume full-colour print, tooling, inserts, samples, and freight. Without a clear specification, buyers can end up comparing different packages and making decisions on incomplete numbers.</p>

      <p>Apex Packaging Solutions quotes <a href="/services/corrugated-boxes">corrugated boxes</a>, <a href="/services/mailer-boxes">mailer boxes</a>, <a href="/services/polybags">polybags</a>, protective packaging, and premium product packaging for Canada and the USA. This guide explains what changes price and what to send before asking for production pricing.</p>

      <figure class="my-10 overflow-hidden rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 bg-white shadow-card">
        <img src={image} alt="High-definition Apex Packaging quote planning image with custom boxes, board samples, print finishes, and packaging cost worksheet." width="1619" height="971" loading="eager" decoding="async" class="w-full" />
        <figcaption class="px-5 py-4 text-sm text-neutral-600">A complete RFQ makes pricing faster and prevents quote revisions caused by missing size, artwork, material, or freight details.</figcaption>
      </figure>

      <h2>Size and structure set the baseline</h2>
      <p>Packaging cost starts with size and structure. A small change in dimensions can affect board usage, sheet layout, die requirements, freight cube, and pallet efficiency. A regular slotted carton, mailer box, folding carton, tray, sleeve, rigid box, and display box all use different conversion methods and different setup assumptions.</p>

      <p>Send inside dimensions whenever possible. If the package must fit a product, send the product dimensions and packed weight too. The supplier can then recommend clearance, board strength, insert needs, and whether the size creates avoidable waste.</p>

      <h2>Material and board grade change both cost and performance</h2>
      <p>Kraft, white liner, paperboard, corrugated, rigid board, LDPE, HDPE, LLDPE, foam, and specialty films all price differently. Board grade also matters. ECT-32 and ECT-44 do not serve the same stacking requirement. A low-cost material can become expensive if it increases damage, returns, or customer complaints.</p>

      <table>
        <thead><tr><th>Cost driver</th><th>Why it changes price</th><th>What to send</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Order quantity</td><td>Setup, tooling, waste, and purchasing power spread across more or fewer units</td><td>First order quantity and expected reorder cadence</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Print coverage</td><td>One-colour marks, full panels, coatings, and colour targets require different production paths</td><td>Artwork files, brand colours, and finish expectations</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Tooling and structure</td><td>Custom dies, inserts, windows, handles, and complex folds add setup work</td><td>Box style, sample photos, or a dieline if available</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Freight and timeline</td><td>Bulky packaging and rush production can shift total landed cost</td><td>Delivery location, deadline, and pallet or parcel requirements</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <h2>Print, finish, and artwork status affect lead time</h2>
      <p>A plain kraft carton is not priced like a premium printed mailer. Print coverage, ink system, lamination, foil, embossing, spot UV, barcode placement, and artwork readiness all affect cost and timing. If artwork is not print-ready, the quote may need design support, dieline revision, prepress checks, or additional proofing.</p>

      <p>Buyers can avoid delays by sending vector logos, colour targets, barcode requirements, legal copy, and any customer compliance rules with the first request. If the package needs bilingual copy, warning statements, or retail panel hierarchy, mention that before the dieline is finalized.</p>

      <h2>MOQ should be balanced against inventory risk</h2>
      <p>Higher quantities usually reduce unit cost because setup is spread across more units. But the lowest unit price is not always the best business choice. Slow-moving inventory, SKU changes, artwork updates, or seasonal packaging can make a large order more expensive over time. A strong quote includes the first run, reorder timing, and expected annual volume.</p>

      <h2>Conclusion</h2>
      <p>The fastest way to get a reliable packaging quote is to send a complete RFQ: size, product weight, quantity, material preference, artwork status, print requirements, delivery location, timeline, and any inserts or sustainability needs. Apex can then price the real package and flag where cost can be reduced without weakening protection or brand presentation.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <RelatedContent items={[
    { title: 'Request a Quote', href: '/contact', description: 'Send dimensions, artwork, and order details for production pricing.' },
    { title: 'Packaging Design Services', href: '/design-support', description: 'Dieline and artwork support before production.' },
    { title: 'Low MOQ Custom Packaging', href: '/blog/low-moq-custom-packaging-100-500-units-without-waste', description: 'How to balance short runs, setup cost, and reorder planning.' }
  ]} />
  <CTABand heading="Need a cleaner packaging quote?" lead="Send Apex your size, quantity, artwork status, material target, and delivery location. The team will flag missing cost drivers before production." primaryCta={{ label: 'Request a packaging quote', href: '/contact' }} />
</BaseLayout>
